      AMCThe famous George Soros quote is =E2=80=9CWhen I see a bubble form=
ing, I rush in to buy, adding fuel to the fire.=E2=80=9D If you watched the=
 stock of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. go up 116% last week, on not much=
 news, you might rationally think =E2=80=9Cboy I wish I had a ton of AMC st=
ock to sell to all these crazy people.=E2=80=9D But you don=E2=80=99t have =
a ton of AMC stock. You could=C2=A0short=C2=A0some AMC stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0borrow it, sell it into the bubble and buy it back later =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
but that is  even crazier: The stock might continue to go up, probably will=
 really, and you=E2=80=99ll get blown up on your short.So the trade might b=
e to=C2=A0buy=C2=A0some AMC stock, at the current crazy price, wait five mi=
nutes until the price is even crazier, and then resell it to someone else. =
This is, roughly, called =E2=80=9Cmomentum trading,=E2=80=9D and it has obv=
ious risks. The stock might go down before you sell it, is the main risk. B=
ut there are other, more technical inconveniences. If you want to buy a lot=
 of AMC stock, it will take you some time. Not that much time =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in the last 10 days, AMC has traded an average of about $6.4 billion wor=
th of stock each day =E2=80=94=C2=A0but some time. Also if you buy a lot of=
 AMC stock, you=E2=80=99ll probably push the price up, making your stock mo=
re expensive. This may not be a big problem (again, AMC trades billions of =
dollars a day), and it might even be=C2=A0good=C2=A0for you (=E2=80=9Caddin=
g fuel to the fire=E2=80=9D), but it increases your risk. If sentiment turn=
s against the stock while you=E2=80=99re accumulating it and bidding up the=
 price, you will lose more money.=C2=A0What you want is to (1) buy a bunch =
of stock (2) all at once (3) without moving the price much (4) while still =
adding fuel to the fire. If for instance you could buy a bunch of stock fro=
m the company=C2=A0outside of regular trading hours, and if you could pay=
=C2=A0a smallish premium over the previous closing price (momentum!), and i=
f the company could then put out a press release saying that your money =E2=
=80=9Cwill be used for the pursuit of value creating acquisitions=E2=80=9D =
and =E2=80=9Cwill allow us to be aggressive=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cit i=
s time for AMC to go on the offense again,=E2=80=9D then the stock will pro=
bably go up some more when regular trading opens, and you can sell your sto=
ck for a quick profit.This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0none of this is investing advi=
ce, it does not entirely=C2=A0make sense,=C2=A0it has obvious problems. The=
 stock might go down, is still the main problem. It might go down because i=
t=E2=80=99s incredibly volatile in general, but also,=C2=A0normally compani=
es=E2=80=99 stock prices go down when they announce that they=E2=80=99re se=
lling a bunch of stock. Also, when you resell=C2=A0all the stock, you might=
 normally expect your selling to push the stock down. But we are not living=
 in normal times, AMC is not a normal stock, and Mudrick Capital Management=
 LP  got this trade right:Even before Reddit day traders pushed AMC Enterta=
inment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s stock up 1,400% this year, Jason Mudrick had=
 been telling the company it should take advantage of the wild rally by sel=
ling stock to stay in business.Now Mudrick has helped AMC do just that, eff=
ectively bankrolling one of the company=E2=80=99s biggest equity sales by p=
urchasing $230 million of shares -- and then promptly dumping them in the o=
pen market for a tidy profit. Meanwhile, his firm was telling clients it wa=
s selling because AMC was massively overvalued. AMC jumped 18% in post-mark=
et trading. =E2=80=A6Raising cash through an equity sale to a single holder=
 is relatively rare in U.S. markets. Having the holder flip the stock right=
 after buying it is almost unheard of -- usually the buyer is an existing s=
takeholder trying to send a message of stability to the market. Mudrick=E2=
=80=99s role in the AMC sale bears a passing resemblance to underwriters in=
 a public offering who purchase shares with the specific intent of resellin=
g them to investors.The involvement of Mudrick =E2=80=9Chas been pivotal to=
 the survival of AMC over the past year, so it shouldn=E2=80=99t come as a =
surprise they threw them a bone,=E2=80=9D Edward Moya, senior market analys=
t at Oanda Corp. said in a message. =E2=80=9CThis was a perfect time to hav=
e a capital raise as the retail army of traders were excited AMC was raisin=
g money for acquisitions and investments.=E2=80=9DThey also apparently igno=
red Mudrick=E2=80=99s dim view of AMC=E2=80=99s valuation. While the stock =
stuttered briefly on Tuesday after the news of Mudrick=E2=80=99s sale broke=
, it still finished up 23% for the day at $32.04.I love it. It was good new=
s for AMC that Mudrick was buying stock. It was good news for AMC that Mudr=
ick was selling stock. Nothing matters.Also the traditional way to do this =
trade would be with an  at-the-market offering: Instead of selling the stoc=
k to Mudrick to resell to enthusiastic meme-stock traders, AMC could have h=
ired an investment bank to sell the stock to enthusiastic meme-stock trader=
s. Then if the stock went up as the bank was selling, AMC would capture the=
 gains rather than Mudrick. AMC  did this back in December, and again in Ap=
ril; I=C2=A0do not know why it didn=E2=80=99t do it yesterday. Presumably h=
aving Mudrick resell the stock rather than Goldman Sachs Group Inc.=C2=A0wa=
s=C2=A0funnier, and doing the funny thing makes the stock go up more.[1]=C2=
=A0Speaking! Of! Which!AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc. (NYSE: AMC) (=E2=80=
=9CAMC=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe Company=E2=80=9D), announced today that it =
is launching AMC Investor Connect, an innovative, proactive communication i=
nitiative that will put AMC in direct communication with its extraordinary =
base of enthusiastic and passionate individual shareholders to keep them up=
 to date about important company information and to provide them with speci=
al offers. Over the last several months, AMC has seen its retail shareholde=
r base grow beyond 3 million owners. With this sizable number of retail sha=
reholders, AMC is taking a groundbreaking new approach to investor relation=
s and investor communications. ...[Chief Executive Officer Adam] Aron added=
, =E2=80=9CDuring my five-plus year tenure as CEO at AMC, I=E2=80=99ve take=
n great pride in the relationships I have forged with AMC=E2=80=99s owners.=
 With AMC Investor Connect, that effort in relationship building will conti=
nue apace even if our shareholders now number in the millions. After all, t=
hese people are the owners of AMC, and I work for them.=E2=80=9DBeginning t=
oday, shareholders can sign up to receive special offers and investor updat=
es by registering at amctheatres.com/stockholders. Investors who sign up st=
arting today and in the coming weeks will be awarded with an initial free l=
arge popcorn usable this summer when attending a movie at an AMC theatre in=
 the United States. The offer will be made available in their AMC Stubs rew=
ards account.Yeah. I have no notes, that=E2=80=99s perfect. =E2=80=9CIf you=
 buy AMC stock it comes with popcorn=E2=80=9D is the greatest capital-marke=
ts innovation of the century so far. I used to work in investment banking, =
building equity derivatives and equity-linked securities to help companies =
raise money and optimize their capital structures, and in hindsight we were=
=C2=A0idiots. =E2=80=9CWhat if we used the contingent payment debt instrume=
nt=C2=A0regulations to increase the tax deductibility of non-cash interest =
paid on a 30-year-non-call-5 convertible bond,=E2=80=9D we thought, like fo=
ols, when the actual way to optimize equity capital raising is by throwing =
in a large popcorn.=C2=A0As of 11 a.m. today, AMC=E2=80=99s stock was up 28=
% to $40.42, an all-time high. It is up about 300% since the start of May, =
and about 1,800% year-to-date. Popcorn!We are going to talk in the next sec=
tion, I am sorry to say, about Elon Musk. Musk is the pioneer here;  I once=
 wrote:What if the actual source of shareholder value, in 2021, is good twe=
ets? Elon Musk built Tesla Inc. into a $600-plus-billion-dollar company par=
tly, sure, by making a big bet on electric cars and then building good ones=
, but also by tweeting all the time, becoming a weird folk hero/villain and=
 amassing an enormous following of retail investors who enthusiastically bi=
d up the stock and finance Tesla=E2=80=99s projects. =E2=80=9CUnchecked twe=
eting by Musk has made it easier for Tesla to secure financing than pretty =
much any company in history,=E2=80=9D I wrote on Monday; it has also made h=
is shareholders a lot of money. When people want to buy your stock, the sto=
ck goes up, creating shareholder value. When people want to buy your stock =
because you are funny and obnoxious on Twitter and they feel personally con=
nected to you, the stock goes up, creating shareholder value, same as if th=
ey want to buy your stock because of expectations about future cash flows. =
Shareholder value is shareholder value.This is not in the textbooks yet, bu=
t it will be. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Surely other CEOs will learn from Musk, no?=C2=
=A0Surely others have?=C2=A0Back in January, AMC and GameStop Corp. became =
the leading meme stocks; retail traders bought them for laughs, to fit in w=
ith their friends on Reddit, and to profit from their wild momentum and the=
 prospects of a short squeeze. GameStop spent the next few months  looking =
very embarrassed about all of this and studiously avoiding talking about it=
. AMC leaned way into it. Aron has gone on a YouTube show to complain about=
 short sellers. He tweets. He=E2=80=99s giving away popcorn with his stock.=
 He=E2=80=99s hitting the retail bid at every opportunity. And he has raise=
d tons and tons of equity financing, at extremely=C2=A0attractive terms, to=
 help AMC not just survive a pandemic that shut down its movie theaters but=
 also to =E2=80=9Cgo on the offense again.=E2=80=9D He has created billions=
 of dollars of shareholder value at AMC not by making good=C2=A0business=C2=
=A0decisions =E2=80=94=C2=A0though maybe that too, I don=E2=80=99t know =E2=
=80=94 but by cultivating the wild enthusiasm of a newly powerful sharehold=
er base, by catering to them with flattery and press releases and popcorn. =
=E2=80=9CAfter all, these people are the owners of AMC, and I work for them=
.=E2=80=9D He=E2=80=99s doing a great job!Oh also, hilariously, AMC=E2=80=
=99s biggest problem=C2=A0is that it has almost run out of shares to sell? =
The right corporate-finance move for AMC at this point is to keep selling s=
tock until the stock goes down; if that means selling $50 billion worth of =
stock and, like, buying eBay Inc. or something then, fine, whatever. If peo=
ple want to give you free money you should take it! Unfortunately AMC=E2=80=
=99s corporate charter only allows it to issue 524,173,073 shares of common=
 stock, and (after the Mudrick trade) it has issued 500,780,240 of them. Th=
ere=E2=80=99s not much more it can do unless its shareholders vote to allow=
 it to issue more shares. It asked them to do that back in March, seeking a=
nother 500 million shares, but then  withdrew the request in April, presuma=
bly because it couldn=E2=80=99t get enough support.But AMC still has the ex=
pansion on its mind; announcing the Mudrick trade yesterday, Aron said: =E2=
=80=9CThis transaction underscores the real value of having some authorized=
 share capital available for us to opportunistically capitalize on sharehol=
der value creation possibilities as and when they arise.=E2=80=9D Yes, righ=
t, if you are a company whose special talent is being amazingly good at sel=
ling stock, it's a shame to run out of stock to sell.Elon Musk=C2=A0doo doo=
 di doo di doo,=C2=A0Elon Musk=C2=A0doo doo di doo di doo,=C2=A0Elon Musk=
=C2=A0doo doo di doo di doo, Elon MuskHow is  this real:Samsung Publishing =
Co., a shareholder in the producer of the =E2=80=9CBaby Shark=E2=80=9D vira=
l YouTube song, rallied after Elon Musk tweeted about the kiddie pop jingle=
.Shares in the Seoul-based company that owns the second-largest stake in th=
e song=E2=80=99s producer SmartStudy Co. climbed as much as 10% to their hi=
ghest level since May 7. The gains have helped the stock more than quadrupl=
e since the end of 2018 as the song became popular. Even a cryptocurrency n=
amed after the song was minted last month.Musk tweeted during Asian trading=
 hours Wednesday =E2=80=9CBaby Shark crushes all! More views than humans,=
=E2=80=9D with a video clip of the song attached. His tweet triggered a ral=
ly in Samsung Publishing=E2=80=99s shares, which, again, underscores the in=
fluence the billionaire co-founder of Tesla Inc. commands on assets from cr=
ypto currencies like Bitcoin and Dogecoin to equities including the so-call=
ed meme stocks.Okay first of all =E2=80=9CBaby Shark=E2=80=9D is probably t=
he best-known and most popular artifact of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0human =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0culture? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0at this point; the YouTube video that Musk li=
nked to has about 8.7 billion views. But you knew that already, because you=
 are alive on Earth in 2021 and this YouTube video=C2=A0is the single most =
famous object in the world. Elon Musk tweeting that =E2=80=9CBaby Shark=E2=
=80=9D is popular adds no new information to what you already knew about =
=E2=80=9CBaby Shark.=E2=80=9DNor is he likely to make it any=C2=A0more=C2=
=A0popular. As of 11 a.m. today=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s tweet =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
=C2=A0reply to a South Park tweet, come on =E2=80=94=C2=A0had fewer than 80=
0 retweets and about 8,500 likes, making it about one one-millionth as popu=
lar as =E2=80=9CBaby Shark.=E2=80=9D More people did the big open-armed =E2=
=80=9CDaddy Shark=E2=80=9D dance move as I typed this sentence than have ev=
er been on=C2=A0Twitter, probably.If you knew that SmartStudy Co. produced =
=E2=80=9CBaby Shark,=E2=80=9D or that Samsung Publishing Co. is the second-=
largest shareholder in SmartStudy Co., then good for you; I did not. If you=
 didn=E2=80=99t know that, though,=C2=A0Musk=E2=80=99s tweet didn=E2=80=99t=
 mention it, so again it=C2=A0added no new information for you.I do not thi=
nk that you could fairly, or unfairly, read Musk=E2=80=99s tweet to imply a=
nything like =E2=80=9CTesla is going to acquire=C2=A0Samsung Publishing Co.=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CSpaceX is going to enter into a commercial partnershi=
p with Samsung Publishing Co. under which =E2=80=98Baby Shark=E2=80=99 will=
 be the exclusive soundtrack for the four-month trip to Mars,=E2=80=9D thou=
gh as I type that I have a terrifying sense that it might happen.The point =
is that it is a little hard to reconcile any version of the efficient marke=
ts hypothesis with the fact that Elon Musk can materially move the stock pr=
ice of the second-largest shareholder of the publisher of a viral YouTube s=
ong by tweeting that the song is good. One needs an alternate hypothesis. F=
ortunately =E2=80=94=C2=A0no, I=E2=80=99m kidding, it=E2=80=99s incredibly=
=C2=A0unfortunate =E2=80=94=C2=A0fortunately I have already proposed the  E=
lon Markets Hypothesis, which says that =E2=80=9Cthe way finance works now =
is that things are valuable not based on their cash flows but on their prox=
imity to Elon Musk.=E2=80=9D If Elon Musk tweets about a song, the stock of=
 any company associated with that song will go up, not because Elon Musk=E2=
=80=99s tweet means anything about the company=E2=80=99s future cash flows =
but because Elon Musk=E2=80=99s tweets are themselves a source of value.=C2=
=A0I don=E2=80=99t like it either! But it fits the facts.Elsewhere in the c=
entral issue of modern finance, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter account: Rememb=
er last year  when he tweeted =E2=80=9CTesla=E2=80=99s stock price is too h=
igh imo=E2=80=9D? He did that after  signing a settlement with the U.S. Sec=
urities and Exchange Commission promising that he wouldn=E2=80=99t tweet an=
ything material about Tesla without running the tweets by a Tesla lawyer fi=
rst. (Because he had previously  gotten in trouble for pretending on Twitte=
r that he was going to take Tesla private.) He then  made it crystal clear =
that he never intended to run any tweets by a Tesla lawyer, and kept tweeti=
ng material things about Tesla.=C2=A0So when he tweeted =E2=80=9CTesla=E2=
=80=99s stock price is too high imo,=E2=80=9D after =E2=80=94=C2=A0of cours=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0not running it by a Tesla lawyer, and the stock went down,=
 the natural question to ask was: Would he get in trouble with the SEC for =
violating his settlement? I thought not.  I wrote:So he did an unapproved t=
weet that drove the stock down by 10%, oops. Does this violate his settleme=
nt? Let me put it this way: I do not expect the SEC to do anything about it=
.=C2=A0The last time the SEC went to court to complain about Musk violating=
 his Twitter settlement, he had pretty clearly violated the settlement, and=
 they still didn=E2=80=99t get much out of it. Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers mount=
ed a robust defense, arguing that interpreting the settlement too broadly w=
ould violate Musk=E2=80=99s First Amendment rights to express himself. That=
 was after Musk had tweeted factual claims about Tesla=E2=80=99s production=
 numbers that Tesla had to correct. Here Musk has tweeted his personal opin=
ion about market valuation. I do not pretend to understand the application =
of the First Amendment to securities fraud=E2=80=94I don=E2=80=99t know if =
anyone understands it=E2=80=94but I am pretty sure the SEC will stay away f=
rom this one, and quite properly.Well, I was wrong. It turns out that the S=
EC=C2=A0did=C2=A0do something about it. The Wall Street Journal reports tha=
t the SEC=C2=A0sent Tesla a strongly worded letter:In correspondence sent t=
o Tesla in 2019 and 2020, the SEC said tweets Mr. Musk wrote about Tesla=E2=
=80=99s solar roof production volumes and its stock price hadn=E2=80=99t un=
dergone the required preapproval by Tesla=E2=80=99s lawyers. The communicat=
ions, which haven=E2=80=99t been previously reported, spotlight the running=
 tension between the nation=E2=80=99s top corporate regulator and Mr. Musk,=
 who publicly mocked the SEC even after settling fraud claims with the agen=
cy.The SEC told Tesla in May 2020 that the company had failed =E2=80=9Cto e=
nforce these procedures and controls despite repeated violations by Mr. Mus=
k.=E2=80=9D The letter, signed by Steven Buchholz, a senior SEC official in=
 its San Francisco office, added: =E2=80=9CTesla has abdicated the duties r=
equired of it by the court=E2=80=99s order.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6Tesla told th=
e agency its lawyers hadn=E2=80=99t reviewed that tweet, which the company =
described as =E2=80=9Cpersonal opinion=E2=80=9D that didn=E2=80=99t require=
 authorization, according to the SEC=E2=80=99s correspondence. When the SEC=
 sought records related to the tweet, Tesla said there were none, the agenc=
y wrote in a May 8, 2020, letter to Tesla. Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s tweet address=
ed the company=E2=80=99s financial condition, a topic subject to the policy=
, the SEC wrote.=E2=80=9CIn the face of Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s repeated refusal=
s to submit his covered written communications on Twitter to Tesla for pre-=
approval, we are very concerned by Tesla=E2=80=99s repeated determinations =
that there have been no policy violations because of purported carve-outs,=
=E2=80=9D the SEC wrote in that letter.Tesla=E2=80=99s outside counsel resp=
onded later that month that tweeting about Tesla=E2=80=99s share price wasn=
=E2=80=99t covered by the agreement, according to a copy of a letter separa=
tely obtained by the Journal. The lawyers said regulators had tried to =E2=
=80=9Charass Tesla and silence Mr. Musk=E2=80=9D with investigations that =
=E2=80=9Coverlapped endlessly.=E2=80=9DThat=E2=80=99s it, though, just a st=
rongly worded letter. I have to say, I think I had the better of this argum=
ent. Musk tweeted something=C2=A0arguably material about Tesla, and the SEC=
 sent Tesla a thundering letter about how egregiously it had violated its s=
ettlement, and Tesla sent back a letter saying like =E2=80=9Cnyah nyah nyah=
 what are you gonna do about it,=E2=80=9D and the answer was nothing.=C2=A0=
Better to do nothing to begin with! If I were the senior SEC official in ch=
arge of Tesla, and I read Elon Musk=E2=80=99s tweet saying that the stock p=
rice was too high, I=E2=80=99d send Tesla a letter being like =E2=80=9Clol =
good one, ya scamps.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99re not going to change Musk=E2=80=
=99s behavior, you=E2=80=99re not going to go to court, why embarrass yours=
elf by complaining ineffectually?I realize that this is not a great regulat=
ory system or anything, but I also want to suggest that Elon Musk tweeting =
=E2=80=9CTesla stock price is too high imo=E2=80=9D does not actually requi=
re a great regulatory system. Just let it go, you know?Elsewhere in Musk=E2=
=80=99s Twitter, my Bloomberg Opinion colleague Noah Smith argues that (1)=
=C2=A0Elon Musk tweets nonsense because it is good for Tesla=E2=80=99s abil=
ity to finance its operations, and (2) this is due to the short-termism of =
U.S. capital markets. Point (1) is, I think, clearly correct as a descripti=
on of the=C2=A0effect=C2=A0of Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter (=E2=80=9CUnchecked tw=
eeting by Musk has made it easier for Tesla to secure financing than pretty=
 much any company in history,=E2=80=9D  etc.), though it=E2=80=99s less cle=
ar to me whether Musk tweets strategically to achieve that effect or just b=
ecause it=E2=80=99s fun and he=E2=80=99s impulsive. I am not so sure about =
Smith=E2=80=99s second point =E2=80=94=C2=A0that tweeting nonsense constant=
ly is a way around the otherwise short-term focus of U.S. capital markets, =
allowing Musk to fund long-term projects at favorable terms without worryin=
g too much about quarterly revenues =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I concede that=C2=A0=
Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter does distract from Tesla=E2=80=99s quarterly results=
. =E2=80=9CThey want short-term news, I=E2=80=99ll give =E2=80=99em short-t=
erm news, let=E2=80=99s see, I can tweet about =E2=80=98Baby Shark,=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=9D Musk could just about rationally think.


